Well, I'm pleased to announce that this is now the official repository for Frontier Creations LTD.

We are a non-profit research group. Our main goal is to create 3d printable medical equipment usable in harsh environments, as well as the equipment to make them (3d printers). We hope to improve the quality of life in parts of the world that do not have good medical equipment available, and are always open to requests, suggestions, or even thoughts on how to make that a reality.

We will likely be standardizing on Autodesk Inventor for the main cad environment shortly. All software will be written from this point forward in some version of visual C++ and wires. All PCB design will be done in KICad. I realize some of those are not free software, but it's proven exceptionally difficult so far to try to design any kind of large scale project in open source software available, especially on the mechanical side of things.

If there is any doubt on the licensing on any design released on this account, it is intended to be open source. If it is tagged incorrectly, please let me know so I can go correct it. These designs are meant for everyone to be able to use, expand, rework, and hopefully help people lead better lives.

If anyone finds anything on the old etsy that they want prior to me getting them repackaged, please message me and I'll make them a priority.
https://www.etsy.com/shop/FrontierCreationsUS

Before I forget, a huge shout out to the guys at https://www.repetier.com/ we use their packages hard to bring the things we do to life, and I wouldn't consider any other setup to do it.

Lastly, our new webpage at http://www.frontiercreationsltd.com has links to all of the appropriate repositories.

Thanks

This is really a long story. In the eighties, and then in the nineties I even patented my idea:

United States Patent 5,506,013 Lesnik, April 9, 1996: Plastic foam novelty items.
Abstract. A resilient solid foam object which has a part of its outer surface scribed
with a series of connected cuts. These cuts communicate with the interior of the foam object.
The cuts are arranged to allow the foam object to be turned inside out and
are shaped to form a three dimensional structure within the solid foam object.
The three dimensional object is displayed upon turning the solid foam object inside out.
A method of making these novel foam objects is described as well.

So, today I have got that 3D-printed!!!
And you can do it yourself with FILAFLAX.

The 3D printer is liberating after being frustrated by materials forever or long as I can remember. The main question being. “I want to design that but how can it be made? What materials could be used? How can the shape be formed? How can I draw up plans? When will I get the time? After watching various YouTube channels I made the decision to buy a printer and have been learning ever since. It’s a great thing. It’s the ease of making the items. Instead of cutting, filing and sanding lumps of wood and never being quite happy with the results its now possible to make something finished looking in a few minutes or hours from an idea to an item.

I work at the Tesla factory and develop cool widgets, fixtures, machines, and whatever is needed. When I get some free time it's nice to hang out in my garage and play with machines.

It would be great to make more friends on here that build things.

If you have something to print, publish your thing, and send the link or an email telling the name and thing number.

As a little girl Monique loved to escape in books and music. She dreamt away in the fantasy and science fiction worlds of the future. In books nothing was impossible.

Monique believes technics can help shape our future. For example 3d printers can enable people to make stuff exactly like they need it. Stuff that can enable them to do things they never could before. Stuff that they can adapt, update and repair themselves. Stuff that fits their needs so perfectly that they do not want a new thing every year. Monique is exploring what 3d printers and lasercutters can do and trying to find out how they can help us create a more sustainable future.
